text.b: Roundabout at Remembrance Road and Wilson Avenue

page.text: For several years, the Michigan Department of Transportation (MDOT) has been planning and preparing to
reconstruct a segment of M-11, including through the intersection of Remembrance Road and Wilson
Avenue. The south and northwest legs of this intersection are designated as M-11, and the intersection is
located within the City of Walker. Throughout the planning and design process, MDOT staff have been
coordinating with representatives from the City of Walker regarding the project. The intersection has a high
skew angle (i.e., the roads intersect at approximately 45 and 135 degrees rather than 90 degrees which is
typical and desirable), and the intersection is currently controlled with a traffic signal. As MDOT was
planning the M-11 reconstruction project, it became evident that if the intersection was to remain under
traffic signal control in the future, the reconstruction project would require significant road and traffic signal
work. This work would be needed in order to (a) meet current design standards; (b) improve traffic
While planning for the reconstruction project, MDOT performed a Road Safety Audit (RSA) for the
intersection. The RSA involved a comprehensive review of the existing conditions at the intersection
including an assessment of safety issues, traffic flow, signal operations, and pedestrian usage. The results of
the RSA identified several characteristics of the intersection that may be contributing to crashes and the
potential for crashes in the future. Some of these factors also have a negative effect on traffic operations at
the intersection (i.e., they contribute to driver delays and congestion). Constructing a roundabout at this
location would address the safety issues identified in the RSA. The RSA also included crash predictions based
on the Highway Safety Manual (HSM), a science-based approach to crash analyses. This evaluation predicted
that crashes per year would be reduced by 52.3% (from 4.63 to 2.21 crashes per year) as a result of
Based on consideration of safety performance, traffic operations, input from local officials, ability to meet
current design standards, pedestrian mobility and safety, and cost/benefit factors, MDOT determined that a
roundabout would be the most advantageous type of intersection control at this location.
Studies and data from Michigan and across the U.S. have consistently shown that roundabouts significantly
reduce the number and severity of crashes, when compared to intersections controlled by traffic signals.
This is especially true of severe crashes which result in serious injuries or death (for both motorists and
pedestrians). Some of the main reasons for this safety benefit are: low travel speeds; elimination of the
potential for head -on and “T-bone” crashes; and simplified decision-making for users. The vast majority of
crashes that do occur at roundabouts are low speed “side swipes”, with a low occurrence of injuries.
The proposed roundabout layout (see graphic below) has been designed to accommodate both existing and
future (year 2035) traffic volumes during peak travel times. As part of the design process, traffic operations
(i.e., motorist delays and backups) were carefully evaluated using RODEL software, a roundabout modeling
program that has been successfully used to design thousands of roundabouts. This analysis showed that
motorists would experience very low delays with the roundabout (less than 7 seconds on average in the year
2035), and lower delays than what would be experienced with traffic signal control at this location. Another
way to evaluate the expected performance of the roundabout is to evaluate the predicted number of
vehicles that would be backed up waiting to enter the intersection (this is often referred to as the “queue”).
The table below compares the worst case number of vehicles expected to be in the queue during the AM and
PM peak traffic hours for the intersection, with either traffic signal control (current configuration) or a
roundabout. A main factor contributing to the longer traffic signal queues is the short length of left turn
lanes (these left turn queues commonly result in complaints by drivers). The results in this table show that a
roundabout will result in fewer vehicles queued than would be experienced with a traffic signal and the

The proposed roundabout configuration has two lanes of traffic in each direction along Wilson Avenue and
one lane of traffic in each direction along Remembrance Road. The outside circle diameter is 180 feet. The
roundabout is designed to accommodate large trucks maneuvers, correct the existing skew angle, create a
low speed environment, and minimize impacts to adjacent properties. The roundabout circle location has
been shifted to the northeast relative to the existing intersection. This was done to minimize impacts to
developed properties in other quadrants of the intersection. Marked pedestrian crossings are planned for all
four legs of the intersection. The roundabout has been designed in accordance with applicable standards
and guidance from MDOT and the FHWA.

The RSA followed the eight-step process which is detailed in Figure 1 below.

M-11 currently occupies two of the originally-proposed four legs of what was planned to be a complete
beltline highway around Grand Rapids; the southern leg was to run along 28th Street while the western
leg was to occupy Wilson Avenue. While the East Beltline was constructed (and appropriately named),
the north leg of the beltline, proposed to run along 3 Mile Road, was never constructed, though it is
closely matched by the I-96 corridor.
With the construction of the interstate highway system in the 1960's, the old designation of US-16 was

along the south and west legs (28th Street, Wilson Avenue, and Ironwood Drive) being designated as M-

A RSA is a formal safety performance examination of an existing or future road or intersection by an
independent audit team. RSA’s help promote road safety by identifying safety issues during the
planning, design, and implementation stages, promoting awareness of safe design practices, integrating
multimodal safety concerns, and considering human factors.
